passages.text: Meituan - 2Q25 Review: Steeper- than- expected profit hit from competition - Buy.

Meituan's 2Q results missed where the intense food delivery competition since May led to a wider than expected fall into losses for its food delivery business for 2Q. Initial market reaction has been negative (with Meituan OTC down \(9\%\) vs. KWEB \(- 3\%\) ) likely due to the 2Q miss and anticipation of wider losses for 3Q. On the positives, we note 1) Meituan's food delivery/instashopping volume growth have accelerated further, and its food delivery unit economics advantage has widened further vs. other players, and 2) the 'intensity' of competition is showing signs of peaking in 3Q for the industry, where we note Meituan has seen improved unit economics for Aug (vs. July). Alibaba's comments in the upcoming results on Friday will be key. 12m TP of HK\$144. Ronald Keung

China Semis | Chips Act 3: China capex continues to grow; migration ongoing despite challenges. We update our views on the semiconductor industry in China for the latest trends post our CHIPS Act 2 report in Oct 2024. In this report, we raise our estimates for China's semiconductor capex by \(2\% - 6\%\) to US\$43bn- 46bn in 2025- 30E and introduce the analysis of Lithography demand in China. We are positive on China Semis development driven by the large home market and ongoing technology development enhancing the local ecosystem, while we expect Gen- AI to drive the development of the domestic supply chain. On Lithography, we estimate 2,261 additional lithography systems are required by 2035 to meet all chips demand in China. In China Semis, we prefer (1) SPE, riding on growing capex and product coverage, and (2) those subsectors with higher exposure to advanced nodes riding on GenAI trends, across IP, design, foundry, advanced packaging, and SPE. Allen Chang et al

Global Autos | Korea initiations, Global EV outlookKorea Autos Initiation - Climbing the wall of worry - Buy Hyundai Motor & Kia; Neutral on Hyundai Mobis. We initiate coverage on Korean Auto names Hyundai Motor, Kia and Hyundai Mobis. Despite accounting for \( 40\%\) yoy (prior: \(+ > 30\%\) yoy) thanks to YTD stronger- than- expected momentum with a solid margin profile, which smooths the volatility at Anta brand/Fila brand. 12m TP of HK\$121. Michelle Cheng

Guming Holdings - Earnings review: Robust growth supported by both delivery subsidy and brand momentum - Buy. Guming hosted analyst briefing post 1H25 earnings release. We came away from the briefing with a positive impression: In the near term, the company's store opening has been tracking ahead of earlier guidance and the per store GMV growth remained robust (Jul- Aug at \(>20\%\) ) supported by boost from delivery

subsidy and new products. Ahead of 2025, despite the food delivery subsidy increased the base, the strong store operation (management expects the store addition in 2026E to be similar to 2025) and category expansion (in addition to coffee, the company has also tested breakfast category) would support topline growth; and we note that franchisee profitability remains relatively stable, despite the UE dilution from higher delivery mix. Meanwhile, the company has been making efforts to enhance brand equity and organization, to pave way for longer term growth. On shareholder return, management reiterated that \(50\%\) dividend payout ratio ahead. We revise up 2025- 27E earnings forecast by \(9\% - 14\%\) , remain Buy with new TP of HK\$32. Michelle Cheng

Mixue - Earnings review: Solid China operations though overseas still in transition - Buy. Mixue hosted analyst briefing post 1H25 earnings release. Key takeaways: 1) The company will continue to solidify leadership in ML China market with further store penetration along with overseas expansion, enhance supply chain and system operations, strengthen Snow King IP awareness; 2) Regarding the impact from food delivery subsidy, management noted that it has boosted volume in 1H which also benefits store level profitability, as well as helping to educate customers. That said, management also expects the subsidy level to gradually normalize; 3) Leveraging the group's supply chain, Lucky Cup brand is set for fast expansion; into 2H, the brand will continue enhancing product offerings and accelerate nationwide expansion; 4) While overseas store count declined in 1H due to operation adjustment in Vietnam/Indonesia market, management noted per store sales had positive growth. 12m TP of HK\$570. Michelle Cheng

Shenzhou International - Earnings Review: Wallet share gain supports order growth - Buy. Shenzhou reported a slight 1H25 revenue beat (3% higher) but OP miss by 1% due to lower- than- expected GPM /OPM from labor cost hike (miss GSe by 0.3pp/0.9pp respectively). We came away from the analyst meeting with mixed takeaways: on the positive side, we are encouraged by the company's still on- track order book thanks to solid wallet share gain at key accounts and a low sales exposure to US market etc., which demonstrates Shenzhou's resiliency compared to the broader OEM universe. On the other hand, a key investor focus - GPM recovery trajectory appears slower- than- expected, which in our view reflects the labor cost hikes in China that can't effectively be passed through to customers, unfavourable product mix/customer mix, and the company's efforts to solidify relationship with customers amid the choppy global demand environment. 12m TP of HK\$74. Michelle Cheng

Wuliangye - 2Q25 First Take: Resilient prints largely in line, with stable topline yoy - Buy. Wuliangye reported 2Q25 results on Aug 29th. The company grew its total revenue/net profit by \(4.2\% /2.3\%\) in 1H25, slightly better than GSE of \(2\% /2\%\) . Implied 2Q sales and NP changed by \(+0.1\% / - 7.6\%\) yoy to Rmb15.8bn/Rmb4.6bn, vs. GSe of \(- 7\% / - 7\%\) (sales better, NP in line). Key surprises: 1) Strong volume growth for both Wuliangye and Series spirits in 1H but with ASP pressure and unfavorable mix. 2) Customer advances remain resilient, increased to Rmb10.1bn at 2Q25- end (vs. Rmb8.2bn in 2Q24, and Rmb10.2bn in 1Q25), up \(24\%\) yoy and slightly down qoq. We think these are quite resilient results amid policy impact and disruption to demand. 12m TP of Rmb139. Leaf Liu
Mengniu Dairy - 1H25 First Take: Core OPM beat with improved cash flows - Buy.

Mengniu reported 1H25 results with sales/NP at Rmb41.6bn/Rmb2.0bn respectively, down \(- 6.9\% / - 16.4\%\) yoy and \(- 3\% / - 6\%\) vs. GSe Rmb42.8bn/Rmb2.2bn. Core OP was up \(13\%\) yoy with OPM up 150bps+ yoy to \(8.5\%\) , ahead of GSe of \(7.6\%\) growth. Key surprises: 1) Liquid milk sales was down \(- 11\%\) and below GSe by \(5\%\) , while ice cream/ infant formula/other dairy products grew resiliently at \(15\% /2\% /12\%\) yoy; 2) Core OPM expansion at 150bps+, beat market expectation with stringent expense control; 3) Cash flow improved: As of Jun 2025, OCF stood at Rmb2.8bn, up \(46\%\) vs. Rmb1.92bn in Jun 2024 mainly due to further declines in raw milk procurement due to lowered raw milk price and improved working capital management. Capex was significantly down by \(40\%\) yoy to Rmb1.0bn in 1H25. The company is hosting an onsite briefing at 9:30am HKT on Aug 28. 12m TP of HK\$23.30. Leaf Liu

Giant Biogene - Earnings review: 1H25 sales/NI inline - Buy. Giant Biogene reported 1H25 sales/NI up \(23\% /20\%\) yoy in line with GSe and maintained full year guidance (i.e. \(25 - 28\% /21 - 24\%\) sales/NI yoy), better than market feared. In addition, we see positive surprise from better managed ROI measured by GPM- Selling expenses ratio, up 0.4ppt yoy (vs. guidance of LSD- MSD% decline full year), leading to \(6\% /8\%\) OP beat against GSe/VA consensus. Per mgmt, besides favorable mix of offline/in- house online channel that carries higher margin, online ROI also improved on LFL basis thanks to relentless effort in optimizing operational efficiencies. Our 12m TP remains unchanged at HK\$71. Cathy Chen

NARI Technology - 2Q25 GPM under pressure, yet positive progress in overseas - Buy (on CL). Nari Tech announced 2Q25 results, with revenue above expectations, but GPM under pressure. We are seeing a GPM yoy decline across most product lines. Additionally, there was a one- off credit impairment loss of Rmb176mn from likely a non- State Grid customer in 2Q25. However, SG&A expense showed stringent control, recording \(13\%\) of total revenue in 1H25, a decrease from \(14.9\%\) in 1H24. Additionally, we see overseas business as a new highlight, delivering \(+139\%\) yoy growth in 1H25, with newly signed overseas contract growing \(+200\%\) yoy. We revise down 2025- 30E EPS by \(4 - 6\%\) , 12m TP to Rmb30.20. Jacqueline Du

Fujikura - CEO conference call takeaways - Buy. On August 27, we hosted a group call for investors with Fujikura's President and CEO Naoki Okada. Fujikura confirmed continued strong demand for its optical products, driven mainly by data center investment by data center and telecom operators. While Fujikura announced capex for a new SWR plant when it reported 1Q results, President Okada's philosophy is to avoid simple repeat investments. Instead, the company plans to optimize production efficiency from fiber production to SWR/WTC processes, aiming to double or triple productivity. 12m TP of ¥13,000. Ryo Harada

Nvidia - First Take: In- line quarter and guidance - Buy. We expect the stock to trade down modestly following an in- line quarter and guidance against a backdrop of elevated expectations heading into the call, as we believe that the upside from Blackwell ramp

has been largely contemplated in our and Street estimates. Management noted that it did not ship any H20 products to China in the quarter. On the conference call, we expect investors to focus on : (1) commentary on customer demand and any supply chain constraints; (2) visibility into 2026 revenue and the Rubin product launch; (3) incremental details on Nvidia's China business; (4) gross margin trends. 12m TP of US\$200. Jim Schneider

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
